# Create Governed Change

Use `slipway new` when the user describes work that should be tracked as a
governed change. This is the primary entry point for governed work.

## Command
```bash
slipway new "<description>" --preset standard --json
```

## Runtime Contract
- Always creates a governed change at `S0_INTAKE/clarify`.
- Sets `needs_discovery=true` when the description implies guardrail domains or
  ambiguity (e.g., auth, migration, "not sure", "investigate").
- Infers `complexity_level` (trivial/simple/complex/critical) from description
  and guardrail domains.
- Auto-detects project context from lockfiles, scripts, and recent git history.
- Skips advisory/question classification entirely.

## Seeded Entry
```bash
slipway new --from-doc <path> --preset standard --json
```
Seeds intake from an existing document (PRD, RFC, etc.). The description is
extracted from the document when not provided as a positional argument.
Discovery, guardrail, and complexity inference use the document content.

## Trivial Entry
```bash
slipway new "<description>" --trivial --json
```
Forces `complexity_level=trivial`, which minimizes intake depth (fewer required
sections, abbreviated clarification).

## Workflow
1. Run `slipway new "<description>" --json`, and prefer `--preset` when the
   user already knows the intended governance posture.
2. Read the JSON output for `slug`, `current_state`, `intake_substep`,
   `needs_discovery`, `complexity_level`, and preset fields.
3. If `workflow_preset` is still pending, run
   `slipway preset <light|standard|strict>` before `slipway next`.
4. Continue with `slipway next` to begin intake clarification.

## Do Not
- Do not ask the user to manually choose internal routing labels.
- Do not recreate advisory auto-classification inside governed entry.
- Do not skip intake — all changes start at S0_INTAKE, not S1_PLAN.
